# WSL Builds Project Context

## Documentation audiences

- Markdown emphasis for prose and tables: [documentation-style.mdc](documentation-style.mdc) (no bold around inline code).
- `README.md` (repo root): End users—what the project is, how to install/configure, how to run **the builder** (`./wsl-builder.sh`), high-level build/component lists. Not maintainer wiring or agent-only notes. Skip table “legends” or meta about formatting (see [readme-user-facing.mdc](readme-user-facing.mdc) and [bash-component-patterns.mdc](bash-component-patterns.mdc) § **Repo root Build List** for agents).
- `CONTRIBUTING.md`: Humans—PR expectations, **Linting** / **Testing** / **CI**, short pointer to `.cursor/rules` and skills for scaffolding. It is **not** the canonical home for dispatch, component patterns, or Build List columns.
- `test/README.md`: `./test/run-tests.sh`, Docker/Bats harness, **build-fixture** and **wizard** test pointers.
- `review/README.md`: **maintainers** — automated advisory builds review (what it does, `src/review/` layout, `<slug>_review.yaml`, how to run Phase 1). Normative contract: `docs/automated-builds-review-v1-spec.md`; further **maintainer-facing** prose for this system belongs here, not root `README.md`.
- `.cursor/rules/` + `.cursor/skills/`: Agent execution details. Build/component/install conventions and root Build List rules: **[bash-component-patterns.mdc](bash-component-patterns.mdc)**. Keep `alwaysApply` rules short; defer depth to glob-scoped rules.

## Project behaviour

- **Terminology:** In prose, **the builder** = `./wsl-builder.sh`; use the literal path in commands, lint lists, and `bash -n` examples.
- Bash **function** names: **camelCase**. Not a package manager; small, explicit changes.
- Builds: `./wsl-builder.sh` `<build-dir> <component>[,<component>...] [additionalargs]... [--force]`.
- Each build under `builds/<name>/`: `conf.sh` (`registerBuildMetadata`), `install.sh` (sources `install-dispatch.sh` only), optional `install_<component>.sh`. Dispatch runs at top level when **the builder** sources `install.sh`. Details: [bash-component-patterns.mdc](bash-component-patterns.mdc).
- One focused thing per component; prefer helpers in `src/`.
- **Systemd / boot:** If an install enables a **start-on-boot** daemon and the script lacks an optional disable UX, **ask the user** before adding `promptYesNo` + `systemctl disable --now`—see [bash-component-patterns.mdc](bash-component-patterns.mdc) (*Optional: disable start on boot*). Do not add without agreement.
- **Caches / large artifacts:** optional `wsl-builds.conf` keys—see [bash-component-patterns.mdc](bash-component-patterns.mdc) (*Downloads, caches*).
- Update **root** `README.md` Build List when user-visible builds change; keep prose end-user focused ([readme-user-facing.mdc](readme-user-facing.mdc)).
- After changes to contributor workflow, test/lint mechanics, scaffolding patterns, or agent invariants, sync `CONTRIBUTING.md`, `.cursor/rules/`, and `.cursor/skills/` only where stale text would mislead.
- Before non-trivial work, skim root `README.md`, `CONTRIBUTING.md`, and the relevant `builds/<build-dir>/README.md` if scoped to one build. For **automated builds review** (`component-review.sh`, manifests, audit scripts), skim `review/README.md` and the spec under `docs/automated-builds-review-v1-spec.md`.
- **Bats** in `test/docker/*.bats` run **only in Docker** (image copies repo at build; no host bind). Before editing `wsl-builder.sh`, `src/install-dispatch.sh`, helpers, or Bats, skim `test/README.md`.
- **User-visible wording** (`printInfo` / prompts / usage / `configure.sh`) can break Bats—`rg` `test/` and `builds/test-fixture/` and update assertions in the **same change**; run `./test/run-tests.sh` when `src/`, `wsl-builder.sh`, `configure.sh`, or fixtures change.
- **Harness vs user config:** Tracked [`test/docker/wsl-builds.conf`](test/docker/wsl-builds.conf). Repo-root `/wsl-builds.conf` is gitignored; `test/docker/Dockerfile.dockerignore` uses a **root-anchored** pattern—do not widen to unanchored `wsl-builds.conf`. If you touch ignore rules, confirm the harness file still copies into the image.
